<ul>
  <li><b>Abashi Favors Necros?</b></li>
</span><span class="newstext">
<p><i>Can we stop this &quot;Abashi favors necros&quot; bs? Its childish to
assume that because I play one that I would drive the enhancement of the class.
You guys want people here who play the game, but when we do, you assume that
theres some class favoritism going on.<br>
<br>
Shortly after I got here everyone was screaming about how &quot;Brad plays a
Ranger&quot; and how they were the &quot;favored&quot; class.<br>
<br>
Im lucky if I can play my necro 4 hours in a week these days. Ive made 4 levels
in the past 9 months. Ill never see 60th level as Im not in it to level these
days. I have only one necro-specific item and it isnt even on that list
(Harvester). Ive refused to consult on most issues related to the necromancer in
house (except for nerfs, which Ive usually been the driving force behind). I
dont really plan to go after any of these items on the list, and I told the game
designer whos working on some really high end quests for all of the classes that
I wasnt interested in helping with the necromancer one.<br>
<br>
What could have been a good discussion fades into yet another thread about how
we must have some deviant plan to hurt your class or favor ours. We dont play
the game on &quot;god mode&quot;, create items out of thin air for our
characters, or run around trying to slip through enhancements for our classes.<br>
<br>
Please stop posting this garbage.<br>
<br>
P.S. My apologies to anyone in the thread who didnt jump on that bandwagon.</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<li><b>Downtime</b><b>?</b></li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
  <p><i>Weve been making so many changes lately, particularly the changes
  related to the enhancement of the EverQuest client, that we need to get them
  online for player use. Sometimes newer changes are dependent upon getting
  existing changes in game, so that player feedback can be obtained and the
  ideas refined.<br>
  <br>
  </i></p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/006993.html"><b>Thousands
    of Twigs/Whips?</b></a><br>
    I would think that the sheer number of people here on the boards complaining
    about it illustrates that there are far more in game than some here think.
    Ive seen dozens of people complaining about it, and considering the
    percentages of people who post on the boards, the number in game can be
    extrapolated.<br>
    <br>
    Let me ask a question: Can anyone here say that those weapons are
    appropriate equipment for the mid-30s?<br>
    <br>
  </li>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/007146.html"><b>Unique
    Quests</b></a><br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: Ive read a lot of the
    recent discussion about camping and item drops and I wanted to propose an
    idea I have had for awhile now. The proposition is to have in game quests
    which follow that same layout as current quests do but instead of being
    constant, they can only be completed one time only ]</i><br>
    <br>
    </font>I assume you mean once per server rather than once per player. Thats
    probably not something that we would do. Wed rather that one-time quests be
    handled on a dynamic basis, with actors playing the NPCs present in most of
    the quest. They involve many people overall, trying to get the biggest
    &quot;bang for the buck&quot;.<br>
    <br>
    It wouldnt be a very good use of time to have several game designers
    spending a week or more of their time to input a quest that operates in the
    standard way, only to have it enjoyed by 3 dozen people.<br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/007149.html"><b>Verant
    wants us to die more?</b></a><br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: Every patch seems to
    either make dying easier or gaining exp harder with a net result that it
    takes a very long time to gain 1 bubble of exp never mind 1 whole level!]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    Id say that very few patches do either, really. Perhaps if someone is dead
    set on camping one fast-spawning NPC, and we change the spawn time on that
    NPC, that might be construed as the former, but were just trying to inject
    challenge into the game.<br>
    <br>
    Every day people post here on the board that the game is &quot;nothing but
    camping&quot; or &quot;nothing but hack and slash&quot;, yet that is all
    they choose to do while in game, when there is so much more there. These
    same people spend 12 hours per day in game doing what they come here and
    complain is boring. Were just trying to remove what is being cited as
    boring. Now obviously we cant please everyone in this process, for instance,
    those who wouldnt be happy unless there was absolutely no downtime of any
    kind, yet we have to try to address the issues that we can.<br>
    <br>
    Just to answer your question:<br>
    <br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: Why do you want us to
    all die Abashi (Verant)?]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    The game should be fun. One of the ways that the game provides fun is to
    provide challenges for you to overcome. Challenges require risk to be
    meaningful. The risk in this case is the chance of failure. The penalty for
    that being death.<br>
    <br>
    If there was no death then there would be no risk which means that there
    would be no challenge and thus no fun. The FAQ explains this in more detail.<br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/007150.html"><b>Why
    Ban Players</b></a><br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: Why not
    &quot;Exile&quot; their accounts to a &quot;bad boy&quot; server. Disable
    their account from access to another server, and transfer their chars to the
    new server.]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    A server really has to have a minimum number of people on it before it
    breaks even in terms of depreciation and operations. Certainly wed save some
    money from an operations standpoint by not having to provide GM support on a
    server of this nature, however it would have taken so long to populate the
    server that it would never have been profitable.<br>
    --<br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: I dont know, Abashi. If
    you ban the bad boys and morons, I think a new server would fill up real
    quick.]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    We might be able to get rid of more of your averagely anti-social people
    (KS, ninjalooting, etc.), however 75% of the GMs time these days is taken up
    investigating scams of one kind or another. Maybe if these slow down a
    bit...<br>
    <br>
    It might sound strange, but 90% of GM and Guide time is taken up by 10% of
    the playerbase. Its the same 10% daily. The real problem here is that when
    someone in the other 90% needs help, they are often in line behind several
    people of the 10%.<br>
    <br>
    Thats why weve posted from time to time that certain issues shouldnt be
    petitioned while in game.<br>
    <br>
  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/007152.html"><b>Guild
    Logo</b></a><br>
    Though this is a great idea that well certainly keep in mind for the future,
    its not something that we would see in EQ for technical reasons. This is
    explained pretty well in the FAQ.</li>
