  <li><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/006559.html"><b>Math
    and Logic</b></a><br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: NO Abashi, its still
    only a 20% chance, since each spawn is independant of each other. ]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    You are indeed correct that each roll has absolutely nothing to do with the
    other. However, the percentages are based upon individual term binomial
    distribution probability. If you have a 20% chance of success (loot) per
    trial (kill), the chances of at least 1 success in 6 trials is just under
    74%. However six trials remains constant. If after the first trial you did
    not get a drop, your chances of getting one in the next 6 is still 74%. If
    after five more trials you still havent gotten one, your chance of getting
    one in the next 6 drops is still 74%.<br>
    <br>
    The probability is determined before the trails, and does not improve as the
    trials are completed (actually gets worse). For instance, lets say that we
    have the situation above. 20% of Frogs will drop the item. Lets say you
    decide that you are going to kill 6 frogs:<br>
    <br>
    Before you kill the first frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next 6 kills is: 73.79%<br>
    After you kill the first frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next 5 kills is: 67.23%<br>
    After you kill the second frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next 4 kills is: 59.04%<br>
    After you kill the third frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next 3 kills is: 48.80%<br>
    After you kill the fourth frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next 2 kills is: 36.00%<br>
    After you kill the fifth frog, your chances of getting at least one item in
    the next kill is: 20.00%<br>
    <br>
    Previous rolls are never taken into account, since they do not impact future
    results. However future results are impacted by the probability success
    versus the number of trials.<br>
    <br>
    You can set up a spreadsheet to calculate these probabilities using the
    BINOMDIST function in Excel.<br>
    <br>
    <font color="#FF0000"><i>[Quote from original post: Yes bad logic follows
    bad logic. Please take a intro class to statistics to learn how bad of a job
    you guys are doing of making what you want happen ]</i><br>
    </font><br>
    I might ask the same of you before you come here to flame.<br>
    <br>
    <i><font color="#FF0000">[Quote from original post: Do this, &quot;/random 1
    100&quot; 134 times, see how many number 43s you get, If you get 0 find the
    closest newbie and bet im 100pp that the next roll will be a 43 since you
    have a 74% chance of rolling it. I bet you go broke pretty fast.<br>
    </font><font color="#072876"><br>
    </font><font color="#FF0000">That is what your logic is saying. that the
    more a number is not rolled the better the chance it will turn up next roll.
    ]</font></i><font color="#FF0000"><br>
    </font><br>
    Thats not at all what my logic is saying. What my logic (and its not even my
    logic, but simple statistics) is saying is that: &quot;I bet that I can roll
    a 43 in 135 /random 1 100.&quot; If the bet was 100pp, and we wagered 10
    times, who do you think would have more money when we were done? You might
    get some good rolls and come out on top, but Im guessing that there is
    roughly a 91% chance (10 Trials, 74.25% chance of success per trial, 6
    successes out of 10 needed to win) that Id have more money than you at the
    end :)</li>
